ic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Care and feeding of bolts and rains...</span><hr size=1> Having just hit 20, I'm confronted with just a bolt and a rain for my damage spells.  Back in the olden days, bolts weren't worth a bent copper, but I heard that they were improved about a year ago to not miss so often.  And I think that rains were fixed to not waste a hit on pets?  Does anyone have any opinions on these spell lines?  Good?  Bad?  Stick to shock of flames for four more levels?  Tips for using them to best effect?  Any help from people more experienced in these kinds of nukes would be appreciated. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uvariathemage.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Varia the mage</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 25<br> <font color=#333333>(8/15/02 9:45:45 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerspells.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1481.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Care and feeding of bolts and rains...</span><hr size=1> It has been years since I was your level, so I can only offer a little advice.  I've never had any problems with bolts.  I remember using the level 20 bolt when I got it and enjoying it while soloing.<br>
<br>
Rains I'm not so sure about.  A long time ago, pets would reduce the number of waves in a rain by one.  Verant fixed this eventually, so rains can do 3 waves against one mob or 4 waves against multiple mobs.  I don't know the damage to mana ratios of the rains of your level off the top of my head, so you will have to do a little math to figure out if it is greater than or less than that of your new bolt.  One last thing.  I've found rains to be somewhat easier to resist than direct damage spells and bolts.  If you decide to give rains a try and are noticing a lot of resists, I recommend you switch back to a DD or bolt since they are more difficult to resist.<br>
<br>
I hope this helps.<br>
 <p><a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=108671>Varia Darselai</a> Arch Mage
<br>
<a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=110669>Milaril</a> 53rd monk</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ujochangaladar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Jochan Galadar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Master Summoner</span><br>  Posts: 492<br> <font color=#333333>(8/16/02 1:48:46 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerspells.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1481.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Care and feeding of bolts and rains...</span><hr size=1>    Shock of Flame is an awesome spell.  It is rather quick to cast, and in conjunction with your ds can allow you to do considerable melee range damage to mobs, while your pet beats on them from behind.<br>
<br>
    Depending on the hit points of the mobs you are hunting, you can use a bolt to great effect by casting on a mob at max range, and immediately recast.  By the time they get into melee range with you will have whacked them with a dd twice.  At that point you can cast your level 16 shock while the mob gets burned by your ds, and gets beat on by your pet.<br>
<br>
    Very effective strategy in your 20's. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/umandrayke.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mandrayke</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#333333>(8/16/02 4:19:38 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerspells.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1481.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Care and feeding of bolts and rains...</span><hr size=1> There is also the single pull factor with bolts.  Bolt spells have a range of 300, while DD spells only have a range of 200.  You can use this fact to good effect to pull singles from a camp outdoors.  Get to a 3-4 mob camp outdoors, line yourself up geometrically, such that one mob is nearest to you and the other mobs are as far away from you as possible,  strafe around the camp to get this distance configuration and back up to just over 300 range.  Slowly move forward, testing wether you are in max Bolt range,  once you get into max Bolt range of a mob and the bolt is flying, backpedal a bit.  With a little practice, this guarantees a single pull from a camp,  in fact if you backpedal too fast, the mob you hit with the Bolt might not even follow you.  Rangers do this trick all the time with long range Bow/arrow combos.<br>
<br>
Mandrayke <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/udurash.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Durash</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 27<br> <font color=#333333>(8/16/02 5:16:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerspells.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1481.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Care and feeding of bolts and rains...</span><hr size=1> I would say skip rains while soloing until lvl50+.  Stick with your bolts and shocks until then.  I can't recall being terribly impressed by the pre-50th rains, though I could be forgetting something.<br>
